1
00:00:04,004 --> 00:00:09,542
<b>You sent a message. It's been read. But no reply comes——</b>

2
00:00:09,542 --> 00:00:13,813
<b>Has that silence ever made your heart race?</b>

3
00:00:13,813 --> 00:00:17,484
<b>Is this silence a sign of rejection?</b>

4
00:00:17,484 --> 00:00:23,890
<b>Or is something still taking shape inside the other person — words not yet ready to be born?</b>

5
00:00:30,797 --> 00:00:37,036
<b>Connecting ancient and modern wisdom like stars in a constellation, finding new perspectives on today's struggles — in just eight minutes.</b>

6
00:00:37,370 --> 00:00:39,873
<b>Tonight's stars——</b>

7
00:00:39,873 --> 00:00:45,145
<b>The limits of language, captured in the words: "Whereof one cannot speak, thereof one must be silent."</b>

8
00:00:45,145 --> 00:00:51,985
<b>Dark matter — making up 85% of the universe, yet invisible to everyone.</b>

9
00:00:51,985 --> 00:00:57,190
<b>The insight that without the other's "face," true dialogue cannot begin.</b>

10
00:00:57,190 --> 00:01:05,198
<b>And an ancient Japanese wisdom: the more something matters, the less you should rush it into words.</b>

11
00:01:05,198 --> 00:01:11,805
<b>Scattered stars, drawn together by a single thread called "silence."</b>

12
00:01:14,174 --> 00:01:18,244
<b>Friday afternoon. You hit send on a proposal to your boss.</b>

13
00:01:18,578 --> 00:01:21,981
<b>Read. But no reply.</b>

14
00:01:22,315 --> 00:01:25,051
<b>One hour. Two hours.</b>

15
00:01:25,051 --> 00:01:28,755
<b>"Did I say something wrong?"</b>

16
00:01:28,755 --> 00:01:33,960
<b>You replay the message in your head, over and over.</b>

17
00:01:33,960 --> 00:01:36,729
<b>The weekend stretches out, heavy and long.</b>

18
00:01:37,063 --> 00:01:41,034
<b>We are more "connected" than ever before.</b>

19
00:01:41,167 --> 00:01:45,305
<b>And yet, that very connection is breeding a new kind of anxiety.</b>

20
00:01:45,638 --> 00:01:50,910
<b>Why do two small words — "message read" — have the power to unsettle us so deeply?</b>

21
00:01:53,913 --> 00:01:58,651
<b>There was a man who thought more rigorously about language and the world than perhaps anyone before him.</b>

22
00:01:58,651 --> 00:02:04,123
<b>Early twentieth century. Vienna.</b>

23
00:02:04,123 --> 00:02:08,561
<b>Born into a wealthy family, a young man named Ludwig Wittgenstein turned from engineering to philosophy,</b>

24
00:02:08,561 --> 00:02:14,267
<b>obsessed with the boundary between what language can say and what it cannot.</b>

25
00:02:14,267 --> 00:02:22,442
<b>At twenty-nine, he wrote a single book — built on just seven propositions.</b>

26
00:02:22,442 --> 00:02:28,381
<b>The <i>Tractatus Logico-Philosophicus</i>. Its final proposition reads:</b>

27
00:02:33,753 --> 00:02:40,360
<b>What is happening inside the other person's mind right now? That is something we simply cannot say.</b>

28
00:02:40,360 --> 00:02:45,765
<b>We cannot know it with certainty — and perhaps we should not try to put it into words.</b>

29
00:02:45,765 --> 00:02:49,402
<b>"Maybe they're upset." "Maybe they hate me."</b>

30
00:02:49,402 --> 00:02:55,842
<b>Those interpretations may not be the other person's silence speaking — but your own anxiety, filling the void.</b>

31
00:02:55,842 --> 00:03:00,213
<b>What language can logically express has its limits.</b>

32
00:03:00,246 --> 00:03:08,922
<b>And the things that matter most — ethics, beauty, the meaning of life — often lie just beyond that boundary.</b>

33
00:03:12,225 --> 00:03:15,361
<b>Now, let's turn our eyes to the universe.</b>

34
00:03:15,695 --> 00:03:20,099
<b>Astronomers had noticed something strange.</b>

35
00:03:20,099 --> 00:03:25,972
<b>By the visible mass of their stars alone, galaxies should fly apart.</b>

36
00:03:25,972 --> 00:03:28,942
<b>So why do they hold their shape?</b>

37
00:03:29,275 --> 00:03:32,979
<b>The answer: dark matter.</b>

38
00:03:32,979 --> 00:03:35,348
<b>It emits no light. It can't be directly observed.</b>

39
00:03:35,348 --> 00:03:39,552
<b>Yet it makes up roughly 85% of the universe's mass —</b>

40
00:03:39,552 --> 00:03:44,424
<b>an invisible gravitational force holding galaxies together.</b>

41
00:03:44,424 --> 00:03:48,828
<b>The time without a reply is not "nothing."</b>

42
00:03:48,828 --> 00:03:53,233
<b>It may be the time your words are being digested inside the other person's mind.</b>

43
00:03:53,566 --> 00:03:59,372
<b>The texts we send back and forth are just a fraction of a relationship —</b>

44
00:03:59,372 --> 00:04:03,476
<b>like the visible stars in a universe of dark matter.</b>

45
00:04:03,476 --> 00:04:06,913
<b>Invisible does not mean absent.</b>

46
00:04:06,913 --> 00:04:09,582
<b>In fact, it may be that invisible time — the silence —</b>

47
00:04:09,582 --> 00:04:13,786
<b>that keeps the galaxy of your relationship from falling apart.</b>

48
00:04:16,756 --> 00:04:23,129
<b>But why does that invisible time make us so anxious?</b>

49
00:04:23,529 --> 00:04:24,864
<b>Twentieth century. France.</b>

50
00:04:24,864 --> 00:04:35,008
<b>Having survived two World Wars, the philosopher Emmanuel Lévinas thought deeply about what it means to encounter another person.</b>

51
00:04:35,008 --> 00:04:37,510
<b>To meet face to face —</b>

52
00:04:37,510 --> 00:04:40,813
<b>that is not merely an exchange of information.</b>

53
00:04:40,813 --> 00:04:43,483
<b>It is an encounter with another being's very existence.</b>

54
00:04:43,483 --> 00:04:46,719
<b>Text messages have no "face."</b>

55
00:04:46,719 --> 00:04:50,790
<b>We send and receive words stripped of presence.</b>

56
00:04:50,790 --> 00:04:53,993
<b>What expression did they wear when they read your words? What was the rhythm of their breath?</b>

57
00:04:53,993 --> 00:04:57,597
<b>We simply can't see.</b>

58
00:04:57,597 --> 00:04:59,065
<b>And so, anxiety creeps in.</b>

59
00:04:59,098 --> 00:05:03,136
<b>Perhaps the belief that we <i>can</i> fully understand another person —</b>

60
00:05:03,136 --> 00:05:06,773
<b>that itself is a kind of arrogance.</b>

61
00:05:09,342 --> 00:05:12,578
<b>We cannot peer inside another person's mind.</b>

62
00:05:12,578 --> 00:05:17,583
<b>And so we can only guess — from the outside.</b>

63
00:05:17,583 --> 00:05:21,054
<b>In his later years, Wittgenstein wrote:</b>

64
00:05:25,358 --> 00:05:30,697
<b>The same "left on read" can mean entirely different things depending on the context.</b>

65
00:05:30,697 --> 00:05:34,967
<b>Silence, too, exists within a context.</b>

66
00:05:34,967 --> 00:05:42,408
<b>The silence of being busy. The silence of thinking deeply. The silence of simply forgetting.</b>

67
00:05:42,408 --> 00:05:46,245
<b>Same "read" notification — completely different meanings.</b>

68
00:05:46,245 --> 00:05:52,719
<b>But without knowing the context, we default to the worst possible interpretation.</b>

69
00:05:52,719 --> 00:06:00,460
<b>The problem isn't the other person's silence. It's that our own interpretations won't stop — and that is the true source of our suffering.</b>

70
00:06:03,362 --> 00:06:07,867
<b>So what should you do when you've been left on read?</b>

71
00:06:07,867 --> 00:06:11,838
<b>Here, let's listen to an ancient Japanese wisdom.</b>

72
00:06:17,543 --> 00:06:24,784
<b><i>Kotoage sezu</i> — the more something matters, the more carefully you guard it from careless words.</b>

73
00:06:24,784 --> 00:06:29,689
<b>In a time when people lived in small communities, face to face,</b>

74
00:06:29,689 --> 00:06:33,559
<b>they could understand each other without relying on language.</b>

75
00:06:33,559 --> 00:06:39,699
<b>Because words were believed to carry real power, they were not spoken lightly.</b>

76
00:06:39,699 --> 00:06:44,403
<b>When you're left on read — who is it that should be silenced?</b>

77
00:06:44,403 --> 00:06:48,408
<b>Not the other person. Your interpretations.</b>

78
00:06:48,408 --> 00:06:55,248
<b>"Maybe they hate me." "Maybe they're angry." — Quiet that voice.</b>

79
00:06:55,248 --> 00:06:58,217
<b>Hold what you don't know as something you simply don't know.</b>

80
00:07:01,954 --> 00:07:07,326
<b>Monday comes. Still no reply to that proposal.</b>

81
00:07:07,326 --> 00:07:10,029
<b>But you pause. You take a breath.</b>

82
00:07:10,363 --> 00:07:15,435
<b>The next time you check your phone and there's still no reply —</b>

83
00:07:15,435 --> 00:07:20,840
<b>before you fire off a follow-up, just stop for a moment.</b>

84
00:07:20,840 --> 00:07:26,045
<b>Instead of listening to the other person's silence, listen to the voice inside your own head.</b>

85
00:07:26,045 --> 00:07:28,614
<b>"They hate me." "They're angry."</b>

86
00:07:28,614 --> 00:07:35,721
<b>Is that really their voice? Or is it a story your anxiety wrote?</b>

87
00:07:35,721 --> 00:07:38,658
<b>Whereof one cannot speak — be silent.</b>

88
00:07:38,658 --> 00:07:43,062
<b>In that stillness, the relationship is quietly, gently breathing.</b>

89
00:07:46,365 --> 00:07:49,902
<b>Look up at the night sky. Orion is shining.</b>

90
00:07:49,902 --> 00:07:57,276
<b>And the universe is held together, silently, by dark matter no one can see.</b>

91
00:07:57,276 --> 00:08:02,248
<b>A constellation of knowledge tells a different story to everyone who looks up.</b>

92
00:08:02,248 --> 00:08:04,650
<b>Don't be afraid of silence.</b>

93
00:08:04,650 --> 00:08:10,256
<b>And try — just for a moment — to quiet the interpreter inside you.</b>

94
00:08:10,256 --> 00:08:15,528
<b>Because it's in that stillness that the real conversation continues.</b>